properties.routewarning: Walkers may be present on two way tracks
properties.description: A super fun, well built, maintained and signposted track system that caters for a wide range of riding ability and is easily accessible. The tracks in this park are on private land and are maintained by the Christchurch Singletrack Club. The CCC ranger team support the club by managing access from the car park on Cashmere Road, assisting with events and updating the track status page.
properties.comment: The park can be accessed via Halswell Quarry Park, the top end of Kennedys Bush Road or from the Summit Road via Kennedys Bush Track.

properties.routewarning: Give way to pedestrians
properties.description: Start from the carpark off Augustine Drive and follow the path that leads into the small native forest. Use any of the several connector tracks to create a loop with the track next to the creek. The second part of the track takes you through open fields and onto a shared cycle path on Curletts Rd.
properties.routeplace: Canterbury Agricultural Park and Nga Puna Wai Reserve
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 1, easiest: Fairly flat, wide, smooth track or gravel road.

properties.description: Best ridden downhill or make a technical climb challenge from the Bridle Path. The track is narrow in places and traverses through some rocky terrain flanked by silver tussock before a final traverse to end near the top of the Bridle Path.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 4, advanced. Steep, narrow, poor traction, difficult to avoid obstacles. Exposed.
properties.comment: At the entrance to Castle Rock Reserve or near the Bridle Path, both on the Summit Road.

properties.routewarning: Give way to pedestrians
properties.description: Start from the carpark on MacFarlane Ave inside the Canterbury Agricultural Park and walk any direction around the outskirts of Nga Puna Wai Lake. The trail is a circuit and finishes back at the car park. Dogs on leash on boardwalk, effective control everywhere else.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 1, easiest: Fairly flat, wide, smooth track or gravel road.

properties.description: Start at Sumnervale Reserve and follow the track markers to a stile which takes you over into Greenwood Park. The track climbs uphill initially beside a small stream before climbing up through a section of switch backs and on through rocky terrain to Evans Pass Road. Cross into Rapanui Bush where another short track will take you to Evans Pass with views out across Lyttelton Harbour. You can return the same way or via the Scarborough Bluffs Track back to Sumner.
Reasonably challenging with steep and rocky sections. Start at Crater Rim Track junction and finish at the northern end of Foster Tce, Lyttelton.
properties.comment: During winter tracks can be wet and slippery so please proceed with caution.

properties.description: A great walk through countryside, this track traverses between Templars Trail and the Isaac Loop Track which connects to the tukaikino Track. Isaac Farm Track is on private land so please respect closures due to farming operations and lambing season (August to September).

This freshwater wetland reserve is one of the few remaining original wetlands that were once common around Christchurch. Explore the wetland on the boardwalk and tracks that circle the reserve and pass by pools, flaxes and grasses.

Te Rauakaaka Trail is a section of the Waimakariri Regional Park that offers significant saltmarsh and wetland habitats. The semi wild setting offers riverside scenery and the Southern Alps off to the west. For a longer walk, connect up to the Templars Island Trail at the end of the Te Rauakaaka Trail.

Begin at the junction of Scarborough Road and Whitewash Head Road, the path heads directly up Whitewash Head via a winding and sometimes steep and uneven path. The track ends at the junction with Scarborough Track, although the section that heads around Whitewash Head is closed, the section leading to Nicholson Park is open if a longer walk is desired.

This track can be walked as a loop in either direction. On both sides of the main valley, it's a steady climb to a staircase that leads up to a cave. The view from the cave back down the valley is superb and well worth the effort. Access the track via Bay View Road and Barnett Park Sports Ground. Moderate fitness required.

A gorgeous short walk alongside the river surrounded by camellias. The walkway is a memorial to the New Zealand women’s suffrage movement who used the white camellia as a symbol of support. Camellias were donated by women’s groups for the 100th anniversary of women’s suffrage in 1993.
properties.comment: Start: Botanic Gardens car park off Armagh Street and finish: Botanic Gardens car park off Riccarton Avenue

properties.description: The Quarry Rim Track is suitable for all ages. It starts from the main carpark and heads up the hill above the old quarry buildings, showcasing panoramic views of the Southern Alps and the city. Information panels depict the workings and historic features of the quarry. The track descends to Findlay's picnic area and back to the main car park. There are linkages to both Kennedys Bush Road and Kennedys Bush Track from here.

Start by going through a gate near the layby on Monarch Drive. Follow the track downhill and continue around Ngaio Point headland. The track leads to Bayview Beach, cross the beach and climb the steps up to Bayview Cresent. Turn left and follow the road to Upper Bayview Reserve, from here the track leads you through the reserve to SH75. Cross the stile and walk carefully along the road back to Monarch Drive.

properties.routewarning: In winter tracks can be wet and slippery so please proceed with caution.
properties.description: The track starts at Tree Crop Farm on Grehan Valley Road. Cross the stile and climb through bush until reaching open paddocks and finishing at the end of Purple Peak Road.

Use the Duke Street track to create a route that links Watlings Track with Bush Rd Track. If you're descending Watlings Track, Duke Street is a short signed track heading off to the right as you make your way downhill.
properties.comment: Watlings Track (start) Bush Road Track (finish)

properties.description: Starting from Riccarton House, walk around Deans Cottage then follow the stone path past the information board and through the wooden gate to begin. Boardwalks wind through native trees, shurbs and climbers and there are plenty of seats throughout the trail where you can stop and listen to the birds.
properties.comment: A tranquil and accessible bush walk through remnant Kahikatea forest

properties.routewarning: During winter tracks can be wet and slippery so please proceed with caution.
properties.description: Access the track of Newton's Waterfall Track at the end of Aylmer's Valley Road - the track is marked with orange topped poles. Climb steeply in and out of the bush and valley before crossing an open paddock. Cross the stile and climb below the crag of teauheke/Brasenose before joining a 4WD track below the pine block to Misty Peaks Shared Use Track.

properties.routewarning: As a working farm, be aware of stock and stick to the marked track.
properties.description: From the car park on Kinlock Road, start on the Te Oka Track, turning left past the gate and crossing the stile. Follow the orange topped poles to the intersection of Bossu and Gap Roads.

This smaller circuit passes through a disused quarry. Start by taking the Orongomai Trail but some way down the descent, turn off to take the Quarry Trail. Almost immediately you will pass under the old cut faces of a small quarry site. Some of the rocks underfoot can be slippery as this is a damp spot. Sidle and then start a gradual climb to meet the Oronogomai Trail. Continue back to the Sign of the Bellbird.

properties.routewarning: On road be aware of traffic

properties.description: Begin at Ferry Jetty and head up a short but steep road to the Caretaker's Cottage. The walk continues on an exposed plateau and passes many more points of historical interest before dropping back down onto the beach and finishing back at the Ferry Jetty.

properties.routewarning: On road be aware of traffic
properties.description: This walk is unmarked and uses existing footpaths and steps.  Head down Foster Tce and turn right at Watsons Lane to drop onto Sumner Road. Head uphill, corss Oxford St and follow London St for three blocks. Turn left on Bridle Path and follow to Simeon Quay.  Cross the road, turn right and then left on Voelas Rd. Walk one block, cross over and turn right on Brittan Tce. Follow until the road becomes Park Tce.

properties.routewarning: Please leave stock gates as you find them unless signage states otherwise.
properties.description: This track starts a short distance uphill of the first gate on Rapaki Track. It climbs via a series of zig zags and then follows a well defined grassy 4WD track. The track exits onto Rapaki.

From the entrance, the track climbs uphill through rocky terrain before a faster unulating section leads into a flowing fun descent. The track contours across the northern aspect of the reserve, offering stellar views across the city and to the Southern Alps. The final section is on a fast gravel surface which brings riders back around to where it's easy to do another loop or head back out.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 3 terrain, intermediate: Steep slopes, rougher sections and some narrow tracks.
properties.comment: Access: Either end of Rapaki Track

properties.description: Start at the corner of Harper Ave and Fendalton Rd and follow the river downstream through the small park. Finish the walk at the corner of Park Terrace and Harper Ave or head into North Hagley Park for an extended walk.
A circuit track with entrances off Beach Road, Mairehua Road and Travis Country Road.  The best place to start is off Beach Road because of the dedicated carpark.

Start the walk just past the boat storage compound at the Akaroa Recreation Ground. Follow the boardwalk along the coastline and enjoy the blue waters of Akaroa Harbour. The boardwalk ends on Children's Bay road, turn left to continue along it. After crossing a white bridge, you'll find yourself on mud flats looking out to Akaroa township across Children's Bay.

properties.routewarning: In winter tracks can be wet and slippery. Please proceed with caution.
properties.description: Walk the 4WD track through Steadfast Reserve for 500m to the start of the poled route. The track climbs steeply to the Crater Rim walkway and Summit Road. The Steadfast gate is not locked at any time.

properties.routewarning: Lambing diversion in place August to October. Please follow all signage.
properties.description: Start near the crest of Gebbies Pass in a car park marked with orange topped poles. The track mostly climbs through re-planted pine forest with views over Whakaraupo-Lyttelton Harbour before skirting below the Remarkable Dykes volanic rock formation and ending at the historic Sign of the Packhorse Hut.
Start the track near the entrance to the Okains Bay campground and follow a well formed 4WD track to Kawatea/Little Okains Bay. Enjoy fantastic sea views along the way.

properties.routewarning: After heavy rain the Oinako River crossing in the Grehan Valley is impassable.
properties.description: From Woodhills Road, climb steeply through bush staying between the two fences. After 1.5 km cross the right stile for a direct route through Tree Crop Farm to Grehan Valley Road or you can continue climbing to the Heritage Park on Long Bay Road. Another route also heads right 200m before the Heritage Park and joins the route to Grehans Valley Road.

Follow the new shared use path from Scott Park in Ferrymead along the coast to Redcliffs. Follow the footpath along Beachville Road around to Redcliffs Village and then take a narrow footway around Moncks Bay and through to Shag Rock. Walking along the beach, meet the Sumner Promenade which continues to the foot of the Port Hills in Scarborough. There are plenty of coffee and ice cream stops in Sumner as well as rocks to climb and the beach to play and swim at.
properties.routename: Te Ara Ihutai Christchurch Coastal Path
properties.comment: Start: Scott Park, Ferrymead  Finish: Sumner Promenade, near Cave Rock

properties.description: Follow the new shared use path from Scott Park in Ferrymead along the coast to Redcliffs. Follow the footpath along Beachville Road around to Redcliffs Village and then take a narrow footway around Moncks Bay and through to Shag Rock. Walking along the beach, meet the Sumner Promenade which continues to the foot of the Port Hills in Scarborough. There are plenty of coffee and ice cream stops in Sumner as well as rocks to climb and the beach to play and swim at.
properties.routename: Te Ara Ihutai Christchurch Coastal Path
properties.comment: Start: Scott Park, Ferrymead  Finish: Sumner Promenade, near Cave Rock

properties.comment: A lovelybush walk on boardwalk through remnant Kahikatea forest. Stop awhile to listen to the native birdsong.

properties.description: This track diverges from the main Blue Track up into the old landfill area. From the top of the hill, catch sweeping views over the forest and ocean as well as out towards Maukatere-Mt Grey and the Kaikouras. The track rejoins the main walk after a few km. There are a number of walks that can be made using dedicated walking tracks and shared use roads that are set out in a grid pattern for wayfinding. A map is available from the Bottle Lake Forest Information Centre and it is recommended to carry one to prevent disorientation.

properties.routewarning: Watch for traffic at track crossings
properties.description: A number of well formed tracks winding through pine forest. Sand hills provide some challenge.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 2, easy: Mostly flat with some gentle climbs and easily avoidable obstacles.
properties.comment: Access: From the main car park.

properties.routewarning: Give way to walkers
properties.description: This track climbs steadily from the end of Hillsborough Terrace, the first section is steep and rutted. The track continues to climb on grass until it reaches Summit Road.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 3, intermediate: Steep slopes, rougher sections and some narrow tracks.
properties.comment: Access from the end of Hillsborough Terrace or Summit Road.

properties.description: From the cattle grid the track traverses through a rocky, tussock and grassland environment. It slowly becomes steeper and faster before it ends at the top of Huntsbury Ave. Built wooden features offer ride around options for more technically challenging sections. Track is mostly maintained by volunteers.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 4, advanced. Steep, narrow, poor traction, difficult to avoid obstacles. Exposed.
properties.comment: Start at the MTB stock grid at the western end of the old Huntsbury Airstrip.

properties.description: A two way track through open tussock land with a mix of earth and rock surface. This track can be linked to form a fun loop using Titus and part of the Greenwood MTB Track.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 3, intermediate: Steep slopes, rougher sections and some narrow tracks.
properties.comment: Start either from Greenwood MTB Track or from the 4WD track that heads up to the Mt Pleasant gun emplacements.

properties.routewarning: Sheep sometimes graze in this area.
properties.description: A two way track through open tussock land. A large part of this track now passes through a native restoration site. This track can be linked to form a fun loop using Knapsack and Greenwood MTB Tracks.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 3, intermediate: Steep slopes, rougher sections and some narrow tracks.
properties.comment: Start from either the Greenwood MTB Track near the old military barracks foundations or from the start of the 4WD track that heads up to the Mt Pleasant gun emplacements.

properties.routewarning: Watch for traffic at track crossings
properties.description: A number of well formed tracks winding through pine forest. Sand hills provide some challenge.

properties.comment: Access: From the main car park.

properties.description: Take a detour from the Tresillian Loop out to the river edge where you can admire the surrounding area.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 2, easy: Mostly flat with some gentle climbs and easily avoidable obstacles.
properties.comment: Access track from a junction park way through the Tresilian Loop.

properties.comment: Access track from a junction park way through the Tresilian Loop.

properties.routewarning: During winter tracks can be wet and slippery.
properties.description: This track is smooth with interesting twists and turns and the occasional steeper incline onto stopbanks or mounds. Parts of the track weave through pine forest and other sections are more exposed to the elements. Either finish through the forest and along the golf course, or extend the ride with the Coringa or River Loops.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 2, easy: Mostly flat with some gentle climbs and easily avoidable obstacles.
properties.comment: Access track from Mcleans Forest car park, off Mcleans Island Road.

properties.routewarning: Give way to walkers
properties.description: Enjoy a pleasant and easy ride on shared use paths around the perimeter of North Hagley Park and the Botanic Gardens.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 1, easiest: Fairly flat, wide, smooth track or gravel road.
properties.comment: Access: Start and finish from anywhere around the park perimeter

properties.description: This track weaves through pine forest and over a few small mounds. Either add it on to the Tresillian Loop to make a longer ride or use it to create a shorter ride with the Gordon Reid Track.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 2, easy: Mostly flat with some gentle climbs and easily avoidable obstacles.
properties.comment: Access: From the Tresillian Loop or Gordon Reid Track

properties.routewarning: After heavy rain the Oinako River crossing in the Grehan Valley is impassable.

After 1.5 km cross the right stile for a direct route through Tree Crop Farm to Grehan Valley Road or you can continue climbing to the Heritage Park on Long Bay Road. Another route also heads right 200m before the Heritage Park and joins the route to Grehans Valley Road.

Rogers Track provides a link from the car park at the end of Hillsborough Terrace up to Rapaki Track. From the car park, follow the Valley Track for 200m until you come to a sign post to Rogers Track. From here, the track zig zags up the hill until it connects with Rapaki Track.

From the end of Mitchells Track near the Bowenvale car park, turn left and take Cedrics Track. The track climbs gently over bedrock and then comes to a junction where Gilpins and Cedric Tracks split. Gilpins heads to the left and sidles through native bush before descending via some switch backs in open tussock grassland back to Dyers Pass Road.

This track zig zags steadily uphill from Bridle Path Road. An elevated staircase climbs above a steeper section. The track continues through a narrower section to exit at Rock View Place. Alternatively, Kenton Track can be accessed not far above the staircase and climbs up into John Britten Reserve.

North Boundary provides an optional detour accessible from Faulkners Track. If you are ascending the track up towards Summit Rd, North Boundary heads off though the bush in a gully approximately two thirds of the way up. It rejoins faulkners a short distance from the top.
properties.comment: Faulkners Track (start and finish)

properties.description: Short, steep track to a secluded beach. Take care on uneven and slippery surfaces

properties.routewarning: Watch out for cyclists
properties.description: Starting from the hospital, Oxford Terrace has become a broad, paved area for pedestrians and cyclists. With native plantings and riverside beauty to one side, and cafes, bars, attractions to the other, this walk is the perfect way to get to know Christchurch’s city centre a little better. The promenade finishes at the other end of Oxford Terrace, past the Margaret Mahy playground where you can walk on either side of the river.
This track meanders through a forested Kanuka gully with a thick understorey of ferns and shrubs. It starts from and returns to O'Farrells Track.
properties.comment: O'Farrells Track (start and finish)

properties.description: Climb the stile at the end of Rockview Place to access Kenton Track or join it from the end of Major Hornbrook Road. Follow the uphill track into John Britten Reserve and enjoy expansive views of the Heathcote Valley and back over the estuary. Take care along the latter section of this walk as it crosses the John Britten cycle track and ends at Summit Road, near Broadleaf Lane.

From the main carpark, follow the road uphill past the buildings. Take the track to your left up to the viewpoint. From here you can look down over the inner quarry and if you follow a track around the other side of the hill you'll get a good view of the park including all the Sister City Gardens.
properties.comment: Main carpark (start) - Viewpoint (finish)

properties.routewarning: On road be aware of traffic

properties.description: At the start of this track there is a small footbridge before the gorge and a diversion heads up hill at this point to traverse above the cliffs through the pine forest. It then drops down to meet the old track and follows the stream to come out onto open farmland. Beyond this point it meets a track intersection where you can continue along the Dry Bush Track or take a left turn up to the Farm Track to make an interesting loop.

properties.routewarning: Control speed, walkers present
properties.description: Meander along the river, through countryside, until you reach the great Waimakariri River at Whites Crossing.From here you can head left along Templars Trail towards Mcleans Island, or right along Te Rauakaaka Trail towards Brooklands.

properties.routewarning: On road be aware of traffic
Give way to walkers
properties.description: A flat, share use trail through a section of the Waimakariri Regional Park. The semi wild setting offers riverside scenery, saltmarsh and wetland habitat.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 2, easy: Mostly flat with some gentle climbs and easily avoidable obstacles.
properties.comment: Access: Off Kainga Road on the eastern side of the railway line.

properties.description: Start from the Armagh Street car park and follow the river path on the opposite side of the Botanic Gardens.  Pass through the Kate Sheppard Memorial Walk, the Pinetum, the Woodland Garden and Daffodil Woodland before coming to the hospital. Cross the bridge, turn left and head past the front entrance to the Botanic Gardens. Continue past the Canterbury Museum and Christ College before turning left on the Armagh Street bridge and walking back along the river to the car park where you started.

properties.description: This track through Rapanui Bush connects the Captain Thomas Track with Evans Pass and the Scarborough Bluffs Track.

This lovely walk begins at the pedestrian bridge on the tukaikino Track. Loop around riparian planting of Plantation Creek before returning to the bridge. This track is on private property so please respect farming operations.

A good connection going from Major Aitken Drive up to Vista Place and Huntsbury Reserve.

A relaxing walk through the Forest. This walk is on a gentle gradient and weaves through the pine & douglas fir trees. Along the way you’ll interact with native wildlife, our resident bikers and information boards on birdlife on the property.

Enjoy restoration plantings as you follow the Pharakekenui-Styx River through Te Waoku Kapuka. Accessible from both Guthries or Marshlands Roads, the Marshlands end is also home to the Kaputahi Community Orchard which you will walk through when entering or exiting the reserve.

properties.routewarning: Sheep graze in the track area.
properties.description: This fun two way track weaves its way in and out of tussocks with one rocky section known as 'Ginger Crunch'. The track is fast and flowy when descending and a good honest climb going up.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 4, advanced. Steep, narrow, poor traction, difficult to avoid obstacles. Exposed.
properties.comment: Either from near the sheep yards at the midway point on Rapaki Track or from the top of Rapaki where it meets the Summit Road.

properties.description: Access the track from Paradise Beach car park. Walk along the beach (a marked high tide option exists) before the track climbs and then descends on the Charteris Bay Yacht Club Road. Follow the concrete road uphill, then take the marked track to Hays Bay. Cross the beach and continue around Black Point Reserve. The track eventually joins a wider gravel track that descends down to Church Bay.
properties.routename: Head to Head: Paradise Beach to Church Bay

properties.description: Take a short walk looping around the river or use this track to connect to the Te Rauakaaka Trail.
