Start at Earnlea Terrace (opposite South Library, Colombo St). Follow the formed gravel path beside the river through the beautiful woodland reserve Ernle Clark. For a longer walk, continue along the sealed path by the river, cross Cashmere Road to reach Cashmere Valley Reserve (30 minutes return).

The track begins 200m from Bottle Lake Forest carpark and winds around the forest and scrublands until finishing in the carpark. There are a number of walks that can be made using dedicated walking tracks and shared use roads that are set out in a grid pattern for wayfinding. A useful map is available from the Bottle Lake Forest Information Centre, it is recommended to carry one to prevent disorientation.
Begin at the observation platform looking out over Brooklands Lagoon. The track follows the lagoon through Brooklands to the mouth of the river where you can join ECan's Te Rauakaaka Trail.

Follow this popular 4WD track from the end of Huntsbury Ave, past Dry Bush Track and up to the Summit Road near Scotts Reserve. From here there are plenty of options for longer circuits via Mt Vernon Farm Park to the east which will take you back down to the city.

properties.routewarning: Give way to pedestrians
properties.description: This track follows the Opawaho-Heathcote estuary edge through Ferrymead Park, passing an important wildlife area managed by Forest and Bird. A flat and gentle walk, keep an eye out for the wetland birds that inhabit the area as you pass through. Be sure to keep dogs on a lead while walking this track as disturbing birds can affect their success in breeding and feeding.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 1, easiest: Fairly flat, wide, smooth track or gravel road.

properties.description: Begin at the Styx Mill Road carpark and follow the path into the reserve. Head right and pass the stunning lakes full of a variety of wildlife. At the fork, the right track leads to a small lookout and the left continues down the main track past a number of paddocks. At the end of the track, either continue on to the Hussey View circuit track or return the same way.

An undulating track that follows the water edge through coastal bush before climbing some stairs to reach Jetty Road.  There is a gate and small pull off area to safely wait for traffic to pass.  If you want to continue onto the Governors Bay Foreshore Track then walk down Jetty Road for about 100m to the start of the track.
properties.routesegmentname: Sandy Bay to Jetty Road Track

properties.routewarning: Sheep graze in the area.
properties.description: A two way track. Climbing riders start on 500m of machine built track with bermed corners and 1.5m wide width. After crossing the MTB sheep grid, the track narrows and gradually climbs through a series of long switch backs to join the Taramea Loop Track.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 3, intermediate: Steep slopes, rougher sections and some narrow tracks.
properties.comment: The track starts uphill of the gate on Rapaki Track. Descending riders can access Elevator from the Taramea Loop Track.

properties.description: This walk visits French Cemetery, the oldest cemetery in the South Island. Start on Rue Pompellier and head up a short steep track through the bush. Turn right at the track junction to reach the cemetery or left to continue the bush walk. Descend the set
properties.routename: L'Aube Hill Reserve and Settlers Hill Walk

properties.description: Begin at the Husseys Road carpark and follow the circuit around the wetland and dog park. The surface is flat with a firm gravel surface making it perfect for wheelchairs and buggies. For a longer walk, create a larger circuit with the Panako Walkway.

properties.routewarning: Watch for traffic at track crossings
properties.description: A number of well formed tracks winding through pine forest. Sand hills provide some challenge.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 2, easy: Mostly flat with some gentle climbs and easily avoidable obstacles.
properties.comment: Access: From the main car park

properties.description: This track diverges from the Blue Track to take a more coastal route before rejoining it after 4km. There are a number of walks that can be made using dedicated walking tracks and shared use roads that are set out in a grid pattern for wayfinding. A useful map is available from the Bottle Lake Forest Information Centre, it is recommended to carry one to prevent disorientation.

From Gould Crescent walk to the Heathcote River and follow the grassy banks down to Tunnel Road.  Follow the path under the bridge and take care not to slip. Follow the trail downstream as it swings around the back of the factories on Settlers Cresent.  Cross the footbridges and continue alongside marocarpa trees to a platform opposite Ferrymead Historic Park. Return the same way.

properties.routewarning: Control speed, walkers present
properties.description: This riverside track has four entrance points - Darroch St, The Groynes, Clearwater Resort, and Roto Kohatu. Linear walks can be created from these to suit individual needs. To walk the full track begin at Darroch St Reserve and finish at Roto Kohatu. Some of this track forms the O21K circuit with the Templars Trail.

Starting from the Museum entrance to the Gardens, walk down to the Curator's House and back up again to the Peacock Fountain. Follow the path along the side of the Museum and the Herbaceous Border until reaching the Central Rose Garden and Conservatories.

Walk or jog along this busy promenade following Sumner beach. Stroll from Cave Rock, which can be climbed or walked under, all the way to shady Scarborough Park where a playground and paddling pool are sure to delight younger walkers. There are plenty of ice cream shops nearby for those hot summer days!
A shared walking and mountain biking track, Thomson Track runs through bush just below the Summit Rd. Connect with the Latters Spur Track for a good route between Victoria Park and Sign of the Kiwi.

properties.routewarning: Lambing diversion in place August to October. Please follow all signage.
properties.description: Start near the crest of Gebbies Pass in a car park marked with orange topped poles. The track mostly climbs through re-planted pine forest with views over Whakaraupo-Lyttelton Harbour before skirting below the Remarkable Dykes volanic rock formation and ending at the historic Sign of the Packhorse Hut.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 4, advanced. Steep, narrow, poor traction, difficult to avoid obstacles. Exposed.

properties.description: From the carpark at Taylors Mistake, pick up the Godley Head Coastal Walk track on the southern side of the bay. The track hugs the coastline as far as Boulder Bay. Take a detour down to the quirky baches before the stiff climb up to Godley Head Rd and the historic WWII coastal defence battery. To complete the loop, follow the Crater Rim Walkway east to Breezes Col and cross the road to the Anaconda Bike Track. After about 10 mins, turn onto the 4WD track and head back to Taylors Mistake.

From the car park at the the end of Bowenvale Ave, walk up into Bowenvale Valley. The track heads up a side valley and sidles along open slopes before descending through pine trees and regenerating bush then exiting near a wooden bridge. Return to the car park via the shared use track or continue exploring up the Bowenvale Valley Track all the way to the Summit Rd.

From the car park, turn right to reach the start of the wetland walk and follow the well formed gravel path past the edge of tidal pools and regenerating wetland vegetation. Either turn left at the first junction to return to the car park or continue along to make a slightly longer loop around Ti Rakau Reserve.  You can also connect to Ti Rakau Drive, Dyers Road or Waterman Place in Ferrymead through the Reserve.

Start from Armagh Street carpark and follow the path north of Victoria Lake. Continue to the Armagh Street Bridge and then proceed north around the perimeter of Hagley Park. Turn onto Riccarton Ave and enter the Gardens via the Band Rotunda entrance. Cross the Woodland Bridge, pass the Peace Bell and enjoy the Central Rose Garden and Conservatories before taking the Armagh Street footbridge back to the carpark.
properties.routename: North Hagley Park and Gardens Loop

properties.description: This short track circles around a former school site in Robinsons Bay. Park on the main highway and walk up Old School Road to reach the area of native bush.

Starting from Armagh Street carpark follow the path north of Victoria Lake. Continue to the Armagh Street Bridge and then proceed north around the perimeter of Hagley Park past Harper and Deans Ave. Head east off Deans Ave and take the path under the oriental plane trees until arriving back to the carpark.

This track follows the Opawaho-Heathcote estuary edge through Ferrymead Park, passing an important wildlife area managed by Forest and Bird. A flat and gentle walk, keep an eye out for the wetland birds that inhabit the area as you pass through. Be sure to keep dogs on a lead while walking this track as disturbing birds can affect their success in breeding and feeding.

Meander around the Matuku Lakes on this gentle loop walk that utilises the various paths in Ferrymead Park. The Lakes were originally designed as a flood retention pond and aspirationally named for the Australasian bittern, or Matuku, which may one day return to Christchurch's wetlands. Wear sturdy shoes when the weather has been wet as the track is likely to get muddy. Please keep dogs under control to avoid disturbing nesting birds.

A great alternative track if you don't have the time for the 11 km Mcleans Forest Track. From the car park, head along the shared track to the right, watching out for cyclists. This winding and pleasant trail heads through established pine and takes you down a wide shingle path that is a bit rough underfoot. From there, follow a shared use dirt path past fields of livestock and climb onto the stopbank. Head left to meet the last section of the walking track along the stopbank and back down to th

Starting from the Hagley Oval carpark on Riccarton Ave follow the path north west towards the Riccarton Road traffic lights. Go south along Deans Ave, turn onto Moorhouse Ave  and continue around to Hospital Corner and back to the carpark.

Follow the track from the Visitor Centre past the Singleman's Quarters to the Christchurch Gardens. Return to the Singleman's Quarters and pick up the track that runs along the other side of the road to the Song Pa-Gu (Korean) Gardens and Kurashiki (Japan) Gardens. From here take the shared use track to the base of the hill. The Seattle Gardens are accessible to the left, the Gansu Gardens are up the hill and Adelaide Gardens can be reached from Findlays picnic area.
properties.comment: Withers carpark (start) - Seattle Gardens (finish)

properties.description: Follow the new shared use path from Scott Park in Ferrymead along the coast to Redcliffs. Follow the footpath along Beachville Road around to Redcliffs Village and then take a narrow footway around Moncks Bay and through to Shag Rock. Walking along the beach, meet the Sumner Promenade which continues to the foot of the Port Hills in Scarborough. There are plenty of coffee and ice cream stops in Sumner as well as rocks to climb and the beach to play and swim at.
properties.routename: Te Ara Ihutai Christchurch Coastal Path
properties.comment: Start: Scott Park, Ferrymead  Finish: Sumner Promenade, near Cave Rock

properties.description: Start from the carpark of the main picnic area and walk around the circuit track on a series of boardwalks.  Finish back at the car park.
From the car park off Beach Road take the loop track clockwise until reaching a junction.  Turn right to reach the bird hide.
A walking track follows along the river’s edge from the playground to the springs, past ponds and through native plantings. Allow approximately 30 minutes to explore and return.

Starting from behind the Surf Club, walk to the end of the cul-de-sac and head up the track. Continue along this track and walk under a canopy of dense trees and bush, take care as the ground is slippery and the terrain undulating. The track will wind its way higher up the cliff and up a number of steps before opening up into a field. Follow the trail and zig zag along the coastal cliffs before reaching Nicholson Park. For an extra challenge, walk through Nicholson Park and down Flowers Track to

The track starts beside the Governors Bay jetty at the end of Jetty Road.  It's a gentle stroll around the harbour foreshore along a wide, gravelled track and is suitable for all ages and fitness levels.

The entrance to this walk is off the access road to Kimihia campsite and well signposted. Follow the track alongside the Otukaikino River through dense bush and past revegetation areas until you cross a bridge to a small island. Loop around the island and return the way you came.

This well marked walking track begins on a dedicated trail next to the cycle track. The trail winds through young pine plantings before climbing a stopbank. Look out for cyclists while walking along the bank. Drop off down a signposted track  and head through more pine and scrub. The shingle track here can be a little rough underfoot. Follow the track over the stopbank again and head into a woodland pine forest. This trail loops around the woods and crosses the cycle track where you will need to

properties.routewarning: Give way to walkers
properties.description: A shorter ride through forest and past paddocks . Once on the stopbank, either cycle along the shared section and come back alongside the Golf Club or enter the Coringa Loop.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 2, easy: Mostly flat with some gentle climbs and easily avoidable obstacles.
properties.comment: Access: Car park at McLeans Forest, off McLeans Island Road

properties.description: From the carpark head along the main path passing formal gardens of Azaleas and Rhododendrons and under a dark canopy of native trees and shrubs. At the end of the reserve turn and come back the same way but this time take the river path that begins near the pergola and follow this twisting trail until you come out within sight of the carpark.

Walk along this shared trail through regenerating native vegetation and exotic plantings by the river. There are many bird species to be spied on the braided Waimakariri River such as bittern, marsh crake and spotted crake as well as water fowl. The 11 km trail has multiple access points including Whites Crossing picnic area, Lorimas Road, Haul Road and Coutts Island Road. Some of this track forms the O21K circuit with the tukaikino Track.

Begin where Estuary Road meets Ebbtide Street and follow the track to where the new boardwalk begins. The boardwalk takes you over the salt marshes where wetland birds can be spotted and lovely views of the mountains and water surround. Once off the boardwalk, walk through pine forest and past South Brighton Park and the Yacht Club. The walk continues along the edge of the Avon estuary before ending at Bridge Street.

Start near the junction of Lake Terrace Road and Carlsen Street and follow the path as it curves around the perimeter of Horseshoe Lake. The path becomes a track once off Lake Terrace Road and finishes about 500m down Horseshoe Lake Road.

From Rockinghorse Road walk past the information panel and start along the Southshore Spit loop track.  The track heads through the coastal duneland before swinging around to the estuary side of the spit and finishing back where you started.

properties.routewarning: Part closure from 1 Aug, track open for 2km. Full closure for lambing from 1 Sept to 16 Nov.
properties.description: From Okuti Valley Reserve, it's a steady uphill climb following a 4WD track through farmland to a saddle.  The track then takes a much gentler descent towards its end near the Hilltop Tavern. The track is well marked but open and exposed so make sure you only go when visibility is good. Due to lambing, the track is closed between July and November each year.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 4, advanced. Steep, narrow, poor traction, difficult to avoid obstacles. Exposed.

properties.description: Follow the Heathcote River from the base of the Port Hills all the way out to the sea. The river meanders through numerous parks and reserves making it an attractive walk or ride through the eastern city. Create a walk out of your favourite section or set a challenge to complete the entire length. Many sections are shared use so watch out for cyclists who may be sharing the path with you.

Start from the carpark on MacFarlane Ave inside the Canterbury Agricultural Park and walk any direction around the outskirts of Nga Puna Wai Lake. The trail is a circuit and finishes back at the carpark. Dogs on leash on boardwalk, effective control everywhere else.

A technical downhill track with some steep rocky sections. It crosses a 4WD track in a number of places and ends by joining the old Bowenvale D.H. which then descends to the Bowenvale Valley 4WD track.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 5, expert: Technically challenging. Giant climbs, narrow tracks, hazards, drops.
properties.comment: Start at then end of Four Pause at the eastern end of the old Huntsbury Airstrip.

properties.description: The track is unformed but well signposted with red markers. Head over open tussock grassland down to Te Oka and Tumbledown Bays and finish with a short walk on gravel roads near the bottom of the reserve.

The beautiful heritage gardens and buildings provide a lovely atmosphere for a peaceful stroll. Walk along the river and enjoy the colourful annual bedding and woodland plantings. The rose and iris garden are similarly stunning spots for a meander.

The track is unformed but well signposted with red markers. Head over open tussock grassland down to Te Oka and Tumbledown Bays and finish with a short walk on gravel roads near the bottom of the reserve.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 4, advanced. Steep, narrow, poor traction, difficult to avoid obstacles. Exposed.

properties.description: This walk heads out to the Waimakariri River for great vistas of the surrounding landscape. Take care as the latter section of the walk is a shared track with cyclists who are often travelling at pace. The walk is 1 km one way.

Meander the walkways in Abberley Park for a peaceful stroll through this lovely garden setting. Pathways run around the perimeter of the park leading you through wooded areas, over a stream and near the rose and fragrant gardens. Be sure to explore.

properties.routewarning: On road be aware of traffic
properties.description: This shared use trail is a transitional walking and biking track along the Avon/Otakaro River. Explore the banks of the river on a mix of shingle and closed roads spanning from New Brighton to the city centre. Take extra care when crossing open roads and always use indicated crossings when possible.

Head uphill, past the regenerating pine forest damaged in the 2017 Port Hill Fires. The track is a mixture of single-track and 4WD roads and is a good cardio work out.  From the top there are spectacular views of Christchurch out to Kaikoura, Lytellton Harbour and Mt Hutt. Free trip down on the chairlift.

properties.routewarning: Sheep graze in this area
properties.description: A short track which starts steeply down some technical rocky terrain before the gradient eases and it weaves through tussock beside the old Huntsbury Airstrip. Some signposted jump features exist and these have easier ride around lines. Alley Express and Huntsbury D.H. start at the end of this track.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 4, advanced. Steep, narrow, poor traction, difficult to avoid obstacles. Exposed.
properties.comment: Starts off Bowenvale Traverse Track near the start of Lava Flow. The lower section can be accessed from the top of the old Huntsbury Airstrip.

properties.routewarning: On road be aware of traffic
Give way to walkers
properties.description: A transitional shared use track along the Avon Otakaro River. A mix of shingle, open and closed roads takes you from the city to New Brighton.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 1, easiest: Fairly flat, wide, smooth track or gravel road.
properties.comment: Access: Corner of Cambridge Terrace and Barbadoes Street, or at the New Brighton Road roundabout.

properties.description: There are several access points to this charming neighbourhood walk: Halliwell Ave, off Proctor Street, Grants Road, Erica Street or Taunton Green. Follow the meandering Papanui Stream through the neighbourhood for a peaceful walk through urban green space.
This reserve contains a set of pathways, intersections and street signs laid out as a street network for learning to ride on the road. Safely practice balancing, turning, signalling and passing.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 1, easiest: Fairly flat, wide, smooth track or gravel road.
properties.comment: Access facility off Westburn Terrace, Burnside.

properties.description: The first section is earth surfaced but after this the track is gravel and offers a pleasant climb through open tussock country.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 2, easy: Mostly flat with some gentle climbs and easily avoidable obstacles.
properties.comment: From either the end of Huntsbury Ave, at the top from the Summit Road or The Bowenvale Traverse track.

properties.description: The track starts with a heart pumping uphill ride to the Summit Road before descending into Lyttelton. Descent is smooth and fast with scattered humps along the way.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 3 terrain, intermediate: Steep slopes, rougher sections and some narrow tracks.
properties.comment: Access: Either from Bridle Path Road or Port Hills Road, Heathcote Valley

properties.description: Track access from Stony Bay and Lighthouse Roads are on steep windy gravel roads and 4WDs are advised. From the car park, enter the reserve through a farm gate and follow the markers along the unformed track as it heads near Mt Berard. The track heads through a pine plantation before dropping steadily to a bluff. It climbs again to reach a ridge and flatten out. Return the same way.

properties.routewarning: Give way to walkers
properties.description: A flat, shared use trail along the Waimakariri River. Enjoy regenerating native vegetation, exotic plantings and the many bird species who frequent the area.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 2, easy: Mostly flat with some gentle climbs and easily avoidable obstacles.
properties.comment: Access: From McLeans Island Road via Haul or Coutts Road, Whites Crossing picnic area, Lorimas Road or Rock Spur car park.

properties.description: Cross the road from Visitor Centre and take the path over the wooden bridge. From here you can enjoy walking the various paths that meander through the plantings and around the wetland. The Halswell Quarry Conservation Area was established in 1999, creating wetland areas and extensive native planting that is now home to a variety of birdlife.
properties.comment: Halswell Quarry Visitor Centre

properties.routewarning: Watch out for vehicles and MTB riders at track jun
properties.description: This track diverges from the main Blue Track up into the old landfill area. From the top of the hill, catch sweeping views over the forest and ocean as well as out towards Maukatere-Mt Grey and the Kaikouras. The track rejoins the main walk after a few km. There are a number of walks that can be made using dedicated walking tracks and shared use roads that are set out in a grid pattern for wayfinding. A map is available from the Bottle Lake Forest Information Centre and it is recommended to carry one to prevent disorientation.
Located within Styx River Esplanade Reserve, just in past the Christine Heremaia Field Centre, the walking track meanders alongside the river past native restoration plantings. Return the same way.
Walk along the Pharakekenui-Styx River to the Styx Loop Conservation Park and enjoy the different stages of plant regeneration from new plantings to ones that have been on site for 15 year.s
A shared walking and mountain biking track, Thomson Track runs through bush just below the Summit Rd. Connect with the Latters Spur Track for a good route between Victoria Park and Sign of the Kiwi.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 3, intermediate: Steep slopes, rougher sections and some narrow tracks.

properties.routewarning: Watch for traffic at track crossings
properties.description: Short section of narrow track traversing the tussock land beneath Summit Road. An alternative section can be added that traverses out and around the obvious line of pine trees.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 3, intermediate: Steep slopes, rougher sections and some narrow tracks.
properties.comment: The track starts at the MTB cattle stops at each end from Summit Road.

properties.description: This short walk loops through the p harakeke (flax garden for cultural harvest) from the car park. Be sure to wander the wider park and enjoy the well established forest plantings and waterways that provide habitat for birds and aquatic life.

properties.routewarning: Watch for traffic at track crossings
properties.description: A number of well formed tracks winding through pine forest. Sand hills provide some challenge.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 2, easy: Mostly flat with some gentle climbs and easily avoidable obstacles.
properties.comment: Access: From the main car park.

properties.description: From the Cashmere Rd entrance, take the path uphill through the Seattle Gardens and up above the Gansu Gardens where there are good views over the park. From there, follow the path downhill until you reach the intersection with the shared use track and follow this back to the Cashmere Rd carpark.
properties.comment: Cashmere Rd carpark (start and finish)

properties.routewarning: Watch for traffic at track crossings
properties.description: Short section of narrow track traversing the tussock land beneath Summit Road. An alternative section can be added that traverses out and around the obvious line of pine trees.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 3, intermediate: Steep slopes, rougher sections and some narrow tracks.
properties.comment: The track starts at the MTB cattle stops at each end from Summit Road.

properties.description: Begin opposite the beach carpark on Heyders Road. The trail is wide and well marked with kilometre indicators.  The track finishes on the beach at the mouth of the lagoon after passing through a pine forest.
properties.comment: Dogs prohibited in the lagoon and on the beach north of Heyders Road

properties.description: Starting at the Cashmere Rd carpark, take the path through the main gate and follow it past the wetland. Continue alongside the Seattle Gardens and up past the Gansu Gardens. From here the track will take you to the intersection with the Crocodile MTB Track that leads up into the pine forest.
properties.comment: Cashmere Rd carpark (start) - Intersection with Crocodile MTB track (finish)

properties.description: The track begins at the Sign of the Kiwi, heading around the Lyttelton Harbour side of Coronation Reserve before re-joining the Summit Rd. Sidle above the road until reaching a small open area opposite a large carpark. Cross the road here to pick up the track then cross again at Worsleys Rd. From here, the track continues to Hoon Hay Reserve and the carpark at Hoon Hay Valley. Travel through tussock grassland and regenerating native bush before reaching the Sign of the Bellbird.
properties.routesegmentname: Sign of the Kiwi to Sign of the Bellbird

properties.description: From the car park opposite the swing bridge, follow the track along the river to the right to get started. The track crosses the road and brings you out of the Groynes to under the bridge. After a stint alongside the motorway, follow the track through the Belfast countryside until arriving at Darroch Street Reserve. From here, either return the way you came or create a loop by continuing along the Otukaikino Track. You'll end up by the Groynes car park, a short walk from where you began.
From Findlay's picnic area, follow the track uphill through the gum trees and the sheep paddocks until you reach a zig zag section that takes you out onto Kennedys Bush Rd.
properties.comment: Findlays Picnic Area (start) - Kennedys Bush Rd (finish)

properties.description: The track starts from a stile on Evans Pass Rd, past the intersection with Sumnervale Dr. Zigzag up under the bluffs before coming to a junction. Here, you can decide to head left to Taylors Mistake or turn right up to Rapanui Bush and Evans Pass. The track to Evans Pass travels gently up through open tussock. The track to Taylors Mistake weaves through rocky bluffs, up past the Scarborough woolshed and sidles gently down to meet Taylors Mistake Rd. Please walk carefully on the road.

This popular, historic track is steep but wide and easy to follow. The panoramic views from the top are well worth the effort. A stone shelter at the Summit Rd commemorates the pioneer women of Canterbury. From here you can return the same way, pick up the Crater Rim Walkway in either direction or continue down to Lyttelton. The track to Lyttelton descends steeply to join Bridle Path Road. Catch the 28 Bus back through the tunnel to Heathcote.
Named for John Britten's famous motorbike, this two way track has a fast flowing descent through grazed tussock grassland and scenic panoramas.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 3, intermediate: Steep slopes, rougher sections and some narrow tracks.
properties.comment: This starts near the eastern entry point to John Britten Reserve. It can be entered/exited at Upper Major Hornbrook Road or Long Ridge Drive.

properties.description: From the Sign of the Bellbird carpark take the Crater Rim Walkway to the right of the carpark entrance and follow for 5 minutes to the start of the Cass Ridge Track.  The path follows a gently sloping a gently sloping grassy ridge to near the southern boundary of the Ohinetahi Reserve. Take time for the short diversion to admire the Cass Peak bush gully. Combine with O'Farrell's track,  Bush Road Track and Ellas Track to make a diverse 3 hour walk.
properties.comment: Sign of Bellbird (strat) O'Farrell's Track (finish)

properties.description: Walk west from Evans Pass along the Summit Rd a short way. The track starts on your left and climbs up on the Lyttelton Harbour side to the historic WWII gun emplacements. Continue along the formed track as it heads towards the television masts at the top of Cavendish Reserve then descends to the Cavendish Saddle. Refreshments are available at the nearby Gondola Top Station. From here, continue along the edge of the volcanic crater rim as it drops down to the Bridle Path carpark.

The start of the track is well signposted and gradually climbs through a rolling tussock landscape to a gravel road. Take the gravel road uphill to some radio masts on the top of Mt Pleasant. A short side trip to the trig offers superb 360 degree views. From the radio masts, the track follows a rocky ridge and weaves its way through tussock to end on a 4WD track near the Mt Pleasant gun emplacements. From here you can walk back the same way or continue along the Crater Rim Walkway.

From the layby at Cavendish Saddle, cross the cattle grid and pick up Major Hornbrook Track heading downhill towards Lyttelton. The track leads you under rocky bluffs before descending through a field of boulders and regenerating bush in Major Hornbrook Reserve. Continue on until the track joins Ross Terrace. Turn left onto Ross Terrace and continue across Cornwall Road. Turn right at Canterbury Road which will take you straight down to London Street.

An interesting link from Lyttelton back up to Summit Road, start this walk from near the end of Harmans Road in Lyttelton. It climbs steadily up onto a prominent spur then weaves uphill to connect with the Crater Rim Walkway and the car park at the top of the Bridle Path.

Start at Dyers Pass Road, opposite the Sign of the Kiwi. The track climbs initially through lovely native bush to a rocky spur where spectacular views across Lyttelton Harbour can be enjoyed. The track re-enters the native bush and sidles steep rocky bluffs to exit just below Bowenvale car park on the Summit Road. Gilpins or Cedrics Track can be picked up from this point to make a return trip to Dyers Pass.

properties.routewarning: Give way to pedestrians
properties.description: Head north from Broad Park along the well-made track that climbs into the dunes and offers fine views of the shoreline. Head through winding tree-lined trails as you near Spencer Park and finish at the Spencer Park Surf Club.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 2, easy: Mostly flat with some gentle climbs and easily avoidable obstacles.

properties.description: The track starts at the end of Rapaki Road. It gradually climbs, offering pleasant views into the valley below. In the mid-section it flattens, then climbs again at a good gradient to a carpark on the Summit Rd. Take in the views of Lyttelton Harbour and the volcanic peaks and ridges of Banks Peninsula. A 10 minute walk up to the summit of Mt Vernon is well worthwhile. You can return the same way or create a longer loop walk by returning via Huntsbury Track.

Start from the main car park in Victoria Park. Take the Eastside Bush Track that descends into Bowenvale Valley, passing through a mixture of native and exotic forest.The track finishes where it meets the Bowenvale Valley Track.

Part of a network of tracks around Sugarloaf, Cedrics Track is on the city side of the circuit. If starting at Dyers Pass, Cedrics Track initially follows the same route as Mitchells Track then veers left, climbing steadily uphill. Cross a stile and follow the track to the large car park at Sugarloaf. Cross the car park to pick up the track again before eventually exiting near the upper Bowenvale car park on Summit Rd. Create a loop by taking Mitchells Track back to Sign of the Kiwi.

Pick up the Godley Head Loop Track from Taylors Mistake car park. The track hugs the coastline as far as Boulder Bay where you can detour down to the quirky baches before a stiff climb back to Godley Head Road. Pass the historic WWII coastal defence battery and follow the track east to Breezes Col. Finish back at Taylors Mistake. Sections of this walk form the Head to Head and the Crater Rim Walkway.

Primarily a MTB track, this connecting route from the Mt Vernon carpark to the Rapaki Track is also shared with walkers. It begins with a short rocky section then levels out as it skirts Mt Vernon just above the Summit Road. The track descends to meet the Summit Road again at the Rapaki carpark. Take the Rapaki Track down to St Martins or return to your starting point via the Crater Rim Walkway.

properties.routewarning: Watch for traffic at track crossings
properties.description: A number of well formed tracks winding through pine forest. Sand hills provide some challenge.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 2, easy: Mostly flat with some gentle climbs and easily avoidable obstacles.
properties.comment: Access: From the main car park.

properties.description: This sheltered walk will take you up towards Summit Rd and can be turned into a loop by incorporating the Rapaki Track. The track starts at the main car park off Hillsborough Terrace and sets off through an area of native trees in the lower valley. The track emerges out into open grassland and follows the valley floor up to a small shelter. From here, it winds up the valley to eventually join Rapaki Track.

Access this walkway from the car park off the Summit Rd near the top of the Mt Vernon Farm Track. This short walk is suitable for buggies and wheelchairs and people of all ages and fitness levels. The track forms a nice circuit on a wide, fully gravelled surface and walkers can enjoy spectacular views over Christchurch and the Canterbury Plains.
The Marette Taylor Track runs along the hillside above the Valley Track in Mt Vernon Park. Combine the two to make a good circuit or use it as an alternative route to access the Rapaki Track.

From the end of Worsleys Rd, this shared use track threads a route along a gentle ridge between pine forest, before arriving at the Summit Rd. The track provides a connection to the Crater Rim Walkway or good loop walks can be created via Kennedys Bush Track or by linking up with the tracks through Victoria Park.

Track access from Stony Bay and Lighthouse Roads are on steep windy gravel roads and 4WDs are advised. From the car park, enter the reserve through a farm gate and follow the markers along the unformed track as it heads near Mt Berard. The track heads through a pine plantation before dropping steadily to a bluff. It climbs again to reach a ridge and flattens out. Return the same way.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 4, advanced. Steep, narrow, poor traction, difficult to avoid obstacles. Exposed.

properties.description: From the car park at the end of Hillsborough Terrace, take the right fork up through the trees and past the cave. The track zigzags up through bluffs on the western side of the Valley and onto a spur. Continue up the spur for a short distance to a panel table. A return trip can be made via the Mt Vernon Farm Track or you can continue a little further to join the Gorge Track. You can also access the Marette Taylor Track.

This track starts on Huntsbury Ave opposite Vista Place, winding through bush to connect with the network of tracks in the Mt Vernon Farm Park. Create a circuit by taking the Gorge Track and Hui Gilpin Track before returning down Huntsbury Track to Huntsbury Ave.

Access the Eastenders Track from either the main sports ground carpark at Barnett Park or at the end of Bay View Road. Towards the head of the valley, a small bridge crosses a creek and the track starts to climb up the eastern flank. Here you leave the old track and follow the new one which branches off uphill. It follows a number of twists and turns to link up with a 4WD track and finishes at the stand of large pine trees at the Summit Rd.

Parking for this shared use track is provided at the car park at the end of Hillsborough Terrace.  From here, follow Dry Ridge Track up and over the crest of the spur until you reach an intersection with a 4WD track. Continue up the easy-to-follow 4WD track which eventually comes out onto the Summit Road beside Lamar car park. You can return the same way or join the Mt Vernon Shared Use Track to connect with either the Rapaki Track to the east or Huntsbury Track to the west.

Park at the Summit Rd layby (the third layby / carpark on left from Sign of the Kiwi, approx 1.5km). Take the Crater Rim walkway heading east for 5 minutes where Bush Rd Track is marked heading down the ridge. With great views of the bush clad gullies, volcanic bluffs and harbour, the track zig-zags tightly to reach the bushy part of O'Farrells track.
properties.comment: Summit Rd layby (start) O'Farrells Track (finish)

properties.description: Enjoy this walk up Bowenvale Valley to Summit Road and then choose a variety of return options.The track starts at the end of Bowenvale Avenue as a vehicle track before becoming a walking track further up the valley, and winding its way through open tussock to Summit Road.From here, cross the road to Cedrics Track and return to Bowenvale via the Sugarloaf carpark or pick up Mitchells Track to Sign of the Kiwi before heading back to Bowenvale.

This urban restoration features native plantings, wildlife, a rongoa (traditional Maori medicine) garden and heritage buildings including an old long drop and a barn that could be utilised as an open air classroom. The walk is partially paved and partially mown in.
Use Bivvy Track for a shorter steep alternative to Bush Road Track and Totara Log Track or combine to create a good circuit from the Summit Road.
properties.comment: Crater Rim Walkway (start) O'Farrells Track (finish)

properties.description: From the carpark at the top of the Bridle Path, head west towards the Rapaki Track. Climb uphill on the Lyttelton Harbour side of the crater rim before turning up towards Castle Rock and Tors Reserve. Continue around the slopes to Witch Hill Reserve before descending to the carpark above Rapaki Track on the Summit Rd. From here you can continue along the Crater Rim Walkway or take the Rapaki Track down into St Martins.

The entrance to Drayton Reserve is on the first hairpin bend of Glenstrae Road. Head up the track and follow the trail through the reserve. There are a number of access tracks leading in and out of the reserve along the way. Drayton Reserve track finishes after a zig zag incline on Mount Pleasant Road where it intersects with Craigieburn Lane.

A lesser used route, Dry Bush Track is perfect for a quiet afternoon in the hills. You can join the track either by following the Farm Track up to the track intersection, or by following the Gorge Track until it meets up. After around 30 minutes you come to a small shelter. From here the track continues up the valley to Dry Bush before heading up the eastern flank towards Lamar car park.

properties.routewarning: On road be aware of traffic
properties.description: There are a number of entry points to Harry Ell from Dyers Pass Road and from Victoria Park. If you start from the rear of the Victoria Park Visitor Centre, zigzag down through the native plantings to cross Victoria Park Road and continue downhill to the junction with the Harry Ell Walkway. Turn left and walk up the well maintained track which climbs gradually through a mixture of native and exotic woodland before emerging at the Summit Road, 100 metres from the Sign of the Kiwi.

properties.routewarning: On road be aware of traffic
properties.description: From the carpark at the top of Rapaki Track, the walkway climbs steeply through tussock grassland to the top of Mt Vernon. From here, the summit ridge clearly shows the volcanic origins of the Port Hills. The track descends to the Summit Rd and traverses through the pine trees in Scott Reserve before reaching Sugarloaf Reserve on the harbour side of the ridge. From this point it's best to take Mitchells Track which takes you through native bush to Dyers Pass and the Sign of the Kiwi.
properties.routesegmentname: Rapaki Track to Sign of the Kiwi

properties.description: From the main Victoria Park carpark, follow the path up to the Visitor Centre and zig-zag down through native plantings to cross Victoria Park Road. The track will lead you below the road through a wooded area with boardwalks and wooden viewing platforms. The second platform is shaded by a large red beech tree - Tawhairaunui is its Maori name. The trail emerges at a carpark near the dog exercise area on Victoria Park Road. Follow the road back up to the main carpark to complete the circuit.

Start from Longhurst Terrace or from the main carpark at Victoria Park. This walk has lots of variety, passing through a mixture of exotic and regenerating native forest. It heads up past the downhill mountain bike tracks and jumps at Victoria Park and finishes with a stunning view over the Canterbury Plains from Sugarloaf Reserve. When you're ready, return the same way or link up with the Harry Ell Track or Bowenvale Valley Track to get back to Victoria Park.

properties.routewarning: Watch out for cyclists
properties.description: This extensive track spans from Southshore Spit to Spencer Park Surf Club, following a trail in the dune crest and winding through the forest by Spencer Park and Bottle Lake. Between Broad Park and Spencer Park Surf Club, the track is shared with cyclists.

Holdsworth Track links Kennedys Bush Track with Sign of the Bellbird and the Orongomai Trail. At the junction near the top of Kennedy's Bush Track, bear right to Kennedy's Bush Scenic Reserve and pick up Holdsworth Track from here.

This track can be picked up after walking downhill on the Cass Ridge Track.  The eastern end of the track leads to the boundary of Living Springs education centre.  Heading east, the grassy track gently sidles around the hillside above Governors Bay for 30 minutes, past the junction of the Bush Road and Kanuka tracks,  before finishing at a piece of private land.  Kanuka forest briefly covers the track with views up to bush clad hills.  Take Bush Road Track to reach the Crater Rim Walkway.
properties.routesegmentname: Cass Ridge Track (Start), Bush Road Track (finish)

properties.description: Descends through dry open grasslands while weaving back and forth with twists and turns. The lower section is well formed with smooth berms that let you corner at speed. Some sections require a decent amount of concentration. Look out for the 1-2 foot jumps off the side of the track. Great views over Taylors Mistake.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 3, intermediate: Steep slopes, rougher sections and some narrow tracks.
properties.comment: Starts on left just past a DOC sign on the Godley Head Road as you head out to Godley Head.

properties.routewarning: Give way to pedestrians
properties.description: From Gould Crescent bike to the Opawaho-Heathcote River and follow the grassy banks down to Tunnel Road.  Follow the path under the bridge and take care not to slip. Follow the trail downstream as it swings around the back of the factories on Settlers Cresent.  Cross the footbridges and continue alongside macrocarpa trees to a platform opposite Ferrymead Park. Return the same way.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 1, easiest: Fairly flat, wide, smooth track or gravel road.

properties.description: Trig V is a spectacular harbourside alternative to the Crater Rim Walway. This gentle, undulating track takes you along the ridge of the Port Hills with breathtaking views of the harbour and across to the ranges above Diamond Harbour. The track returns to the Crater Rim Walkway near a layby off the Summit Rd. From here you can continue on the Walkway or return to Governors Bay via Watlings Track.
properties.comment: Faulkners Track, Summit Rd (start0 near Watlings Track, Summit Rd (finish)

properties.routeshareduse: No, except for end of track.
properties.routewarning: Punctures common. Make sure you've got a good back tire or spare tubes.
properties.description: Highly technical downhill track descending an exposed rocky ridge. After a series of steep chutes, the track enters a regenerating bush site.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 6, extreme: Downhill/free ride. Steep, large drop offs, unavoidable obstacles.
properties.comment: Off the Bowenvale Traverse Track at a rocky corner.

properties.description: This alternative to O'Farrells track is steep and narrow, leading downhill from O'Farrells track to a small stream with regenerating native forest. Beware the blackberry on the grassy slopes. Wai-iti means small stream.
properties.comment: O'Farrells Track (start and finsih)

properties.description: The track begins on your left, just off Lighthouse Land. Head steadily up through the subdivision before zig-zagging through scrub and new plantings to reach the junction with South Boundary. Continue up a steep narrow path through rocky bluffs and into a bush gully past the North Boundary junction. Further on, take a short detour to a spectacular lookout point. The track meets Trig V as it crests the ridgeline. Link up with the Crater Rim Walkway or walk a little further to the Summit Road.
properties.comment: Lighthouse Lane (Start) Trig V near Summit Rd (finish)

properties.description: Park at the Summit Road layby (the third layby / carpark on left from Sign of the Kiwi, approx 1.5km).  Take the Crater Rim Walkway heading west for a short distance before joining Ellas Track.  From here, the track sidles below volcanic bluffs overlooking Lyttleton Harbour.  After meeting another junction with the Crater Rim Walkway, the track becomes rockier before emerging at a large open grassy area below the Sign of the Bellbird carpark.  After a further 10 minutes you will join Cass Ridge
properties.comment: Summit Road layby (start) Cass Ridge Track (finish)

properties.description: Start near the steps below the Sign of the Kiwi and pick up the track to the left above Dyers Pass Road. Follow the track as it skirts around scrubby slopes high above Lyttelton Harbour before turning back to the Summit Road near a large gravel car park. Complete the circuit and return to the Sign of the Kiwi by picking up the track to the left that sidles above the Summit Road and ends near the cattlestop by the Sign of the Kiwi car park.

A lovely circuit that climbs gently uphill to offer stunning views out across the city and links to Linda Woods Reserve and the walking tracks there. The circuit then meanders downhill through established native plantings and around the perimeter of the Pony Club before exiting onto the main road. Head right to go back to the car park you started from.
properties.comment: Not accessible, stile crossing present.

properties.description: Totara Log Track connects Bush Road, Bivvy and Ellas tracks to enable a variety of shorter loops around the central and western parts of Ohinetahi Reserve.
properties.comment: Bush Road Track (start) Ellas Track (Finish)

properties.description: As you descend on Titoki Track from the junction with South Boundary, the track zig-zags steeply through regenerating bush. The descent evens out as you enter a bush covered gully. Follow the watercourse down through a pocket of fuchsia forest, past the junction with Ngaio Track and out to Bay Heights. From here follow the roadside footpaths down into Governors Bay.
properties.comment: South Boundary (Start) Bay Heights, Governors Bay (finish)

properties.description: This track provides an enjoyable low gradient climb out of Taylors Mistake. The track is on private land and was built by Ground Effect Ltd and volunteers (who continue to maintain it). It is most commonly used as a climbing track and is a great way back to the top if you've come down Anaconda into Taylors Mistake.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 3, intermediate: Steep slopes, rougher sections and some narrow tracks.
properties.comment: Start near the main car park at Taylors Mistake. Can also be accessed from the Godley Head Road at Livingstone Col.

properties.description: South Boundary provides a useful method of connecting Bush Road Track with Watlings, Titoki and Faulkners Tracks in order to create a number of walking route options. Create a loop that suits you depending on whether you're starting from the Summit Road or Governors Bay.
properties.comment: Bush Rd Track (Start) Faulkners Track (Finish)

properties.description: A short circuit joining the main track at the bottom and midway up the hill. This track was originally created to facilitate volunteer restoration planting but is a pleasant little loop or a good shortcut back to the car park.

properties.routewarning: Do not ride this track uphill
properties.description: A local favourite with bermed corners - some of which are paved with Haslwell Quarry stone. Some small jump features exist with ride around options available. It's fast and flowy and makes a very good progression track to move up the grades. This track is maintained by the ranger team and volunteers down as far as the Christchurch Adventure Park Summit connector track. The old lower section of Flying Nun is now maintained by the Christchurch Adventure Park.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 4, advanced. Steep, narrow, poor traction, difficult to avoid obstacles. Exposed.
properties.comment: Access by riding 400m up a 4WD track near the top of Worsleys Road off the Summit Road.

properties.routewarning: Please follow summer dog rules between flags and keep dogs from disturbing wildlife and beach users.
properties.description: This extensive track spans from Southshore Spit to Spencer Park Surf Club, following a trail in the dune crest and winding through the forest by Spencer Park and Bottle Lake. Between Broad Park and Spencer Park Surf Club, the track is shared with cyclists.

The track can be started at Halswell Quarry or at the end of Kennedys Bush Rd. Mostly on a wide 4WD surface, the shared use track starts with a steady climb and then flattens and descends to a gate. From the gate it's all uphill to the Summit Road. Cross the road and follow the Crater Rim a short way for views down Lyttelton Harbour. The track is mostly through private land. Stay on the track and be mindful that cattle can be grazing alongside it. Lambing is between August and September.

While Titoki Track largely follows a bush covered stream gully, Ngaio Track offers a pleasant alternative route mostly along a more open ridge. If descending, you leave Tikoki Track shortly after the junction with South Boundary and rejoin close to the end of the track at Bay Heights.
properties.comment: Tikoki Track (start and finish)

properties.routewarning: Sheep graze in the area
properties.description: A two way single track weaving through open tussock grassland just below the Summit Road. Starting from the Huntsbury Track end, it descends more steeply and is faster to ride.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 3, intermediate: Steep slopes, rougher sections and some narrow tracks.
properties.comment: Either at Thompsons car park or from the top of Huntsbury Track, both off the Summit Road.

properties.description: Watlings Track requires some surefootedness as it takes you down a steep, bouldery, bush-covered gully.  It makes a wonderful contrast to the usual open landscapes of the Port Hills. You can connect with the Bush Road Track via Duke Street, a short track to heading off to the right as you make your way downhill. Shortly after that junction, you'll pop out onto an open spur where you can choose to follow the South Boundary back to Faulkners Track or take Titoki Track down to Governors Bay.
properties.comment: Summit Rd near Trig V Track (start) South boundary (finish)

properties.description: This track can be walked as a loop in either direction. On both sides of the main valley, it's a steady climb to a staircase that leads up to a cave. The view from the cave back down the valley is superb and well worth the effort. Access the track via Bay View Road and Barnett Park Sports Ground. Moderate fitness required.

The first part of this track through Cass Peak Reserve is currently closed due to the earthquakes. Walk carefully south along the side of the Summit Road for about 1km until you reach a cattle grid marking the point where you can access the track. Continue south until arriving at the slopes of Coopers Knob/ Omawete, the highest point on the Port Hills and breathtaking views. A descent through native bush brings you to the end of the Crater Rim Walkway at a car park opposite Ahururi Reserve.
properties.routesegmentname: Sign of the Bellbird to Ahuriri Reserve

properties.routewarning: Give way to walkers
properties.description: Ride up Rapaki Road to start the gravel track. The track climbs gradually and two MTB cattle grids are crossed before exiting at another cattle grid near Summit Road. Alternatives to riding this busy track include the nearby Elevator and Full Monty Tracks.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 3, intermediate: Steep slopes, rougher sections and some narrow tracks.
properties.comment: Start from the end of Rapaki or Summit Road.

properties.description: A short two way technical track that weaves its way through mostly rocky terrain.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 4, advanced. Steep, narrow, poor traction, difficult to avoid obstacles. Exposed.
properties.comment: From either the locked vehicle gate on the Summit Road near the top of Rapaki Track (it's a short 70m climb up a shared use track) or it can also be accessed from its eastern end on the Summit Road.

properties.description: Omawete-Coopers Knob is the highest point on the Port Hills (573m) and offers panoramic views over the plains and up Lyttelton Harbour. You can pick up the track directly from the Summit Road, just north of the Gibraltar Rock car park. The track encircles the summit (which is a short detour from the Crater Rim Walkway and requires some easy rock scrambling) before heading back towards Summit Road and the car park.

Climbs gradually uphill through tussock slopes and a short section of gravel road. Cross two more stiles and then ride down to where it joins the Greenwood Park Track. Some sections are narrow with technical rocky sections. The Greenwood Park Track then descends down to Evans Pass.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 4, advanced. Steep, narrow, poor traction, difficult to avoid obstacles. Exposed.
properties.comment: From Cavendish Saddle at the layby beside Summit Road, follow the red capped markers to a walkover stile. Can also be accessed by riding up Broadleaf Lane from the Summit Road.

properties.description: Start at the Sign of the Bellbird and follow a grassy track to a stile. Cross, and zigzag down through bush. Below the Quarry Trail junction the track becomes rougher and descends to a small stream. The lower part of the reserve has some of the best accessible forest in the Port Hills with several large totara and matai trees. The track starts climbing up beside a stream, through predominantly kanuka forest, back to the Sign of the Bellbird.

A wide well formed track that follows the coastline above the shore and passes Magazine and Corsair Bay before arriving at Cass Bay.  From Cass Bay, follow a track above the playground to enter Pony Point Reserve which offers a circuit walk with great harbour views.

This walk offers dramatic rocky landscapes and magical views. From the Godley Head car park head up toward Breezes Col as the track rises onto the Lyttelton Harbour side and follows a ridge. The track runs along a stock fence before heading down to Godley Head Road. Just over the last cattle grid you’ll find the Evans Pass car park.

properties.routewarning: Give way to walkers
properties.description: Descends down a wide, rough and rutted 4WD track. Near a pylon tower, the track becomes a traversing single track that gets progressively steeper and finishes with a series of fun switchbacks leading onto the Bowenvale 4WD track. From there it's a short ride to Bowenvale Ave.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 4, advanced. Steep, narrow, poor traction, difficult to avoid obstacles. Exposed.
properties.comment: Start at the top of the Huntsbury Airstrip.

properties.routewarning: Sheep graze in this area
properties.description: The track is ridden in an anti-clockwise direction to help take full advantage of the prevailing north easterly wind in summer. It starts with a gentle switchback climb with some rocky sections to the high point. It then descends through the fast flowy sections before turning south west and contouring all the way back around to its start.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 3, intermediate: Steep slopes, rougher sections and some narrow tracks.
properties.comment: The main entrance point is halfway on Rapaki Track at the entrance to Montgomery Reserve. It can also be accessed by riding up Elevator.

properties.routewarning: Give way to walkers. Track very slippery after rain and in winter.
properties.description: A nice long descent or ascent on an obvious 4WD track which is mostly double fenced. Has a couple of steep pinches in places.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 3, intermediate: Steep slopes, rougher sections and some narrow tracks.
properties.comment: Via C2 and Crocodile Up Track from the Crocodile XC Park. Can also be accessed from Kennedys Bush Road or down from the Summit Road.

properties.routewarning: Give way to walkers. Sheep graze in area. Isolated - ensure preparedness.
properties.description: Rocky and very technical in places. Some fast flowy sections through open tussock and grassland where sheep often graze. Panoramic views and the track can be ridden both ways.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 4, advanced. Steep, narrow, poor traction, difficult to avoid obstacles. Exposed
properties.comment: Near Evans Pass or at the DOC car park at Godley Head. Access also gained via Taylors Escape Track.

properties.description: The track starts beside the Governors Bay jetty at the end of Jetty Road.  It's a gentle ride around the harbour foreshore along a wide, gravelled track and is suitable for all ages and fitness levels.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 1, easiest: Fairly flat, wide, smooth track or gravel road.

properties.routewarning: This track has exposed steep cliff edges in places
properties.description: From Church Bay, follow an old road line through pine trees above the cliffs. Caution is needed as there are muddy and difficult sections under foot. Diamond Harbour boasts a swimming beach, cafes and is also home to the historic Stoddart Cottage, birthplace of Margaret Stoddart - one of New Zealand's foremost flower and landscape painters. The walk can also be done in reverse if you've arrived on the Diamond Harbour ferry.
properties.routename: Coastal Cliff Walk: Church Bay to Diamond Harbour Wharf

properties.routewarning: Please give way to walkers and runners and look out for livestock.
properties.description: A great connecting track between Full Monty MTB and Bowenvale Traverse MTB. It mostly climbs from the Rapaki end and is downhill from the Huntsbury 4WD track end.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 3, intermediate: Steep slopes, rougher sections and some narrow tracks.
properties.comment: A two way track. Entrance points are from the top of Huntsbury 4WD and Rapaki Tracks near the Summit Road.

properties.routewarning: This track has exposed steep cliff edges in places
properties.description: Head up the steps by the wharf and take the track around Te-Upoko-o-Kuri/Stoddart Point. See stunning views of the harbour and Ripapa Island, once an important pa site for Ngai Tahu and later a quarantine station, prison and fort. The track emerges on Purau Ave just shy of the bay - follow the road to reach the sandy beach.
properties.routename: Coastal Cliffs Walk: Diamond Harbour to Purau Bay

properties.routewarning: Part closure from 1 Aug, track open for 2km. Full closure for lambing from 1 Sept to 16 Nov.
properties.description: From Okuti Valley Reserve, it's a steady uphill climb following a 4WD track through farmland to a saddle.  The track then takes a much gentler descent towards its end near the Hilltop Tavern. The track is well marked but open and exposed so make sure you only go when visibility is good. Due to lambing, the track is closed between July and November each year.
A short loop walk through native bush. It is best accessed from the Summit Road layby below the old Jollies Bush stone shelter. The track can be used to connect with the Mt Pleasant Connector Track.

properties.routewarning: During winter tracks can be wet and slippery.
properties.description: This track is smooth with interesting twists and turns and the occasional steeper incline onto stopbanks or mounds. Parts of the track weave through pine forest and other sections are more exposed to the elements. Either finish through the forest and along the golf course, or extend the ride with the Coringa Loop.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 2, easy: Mostly flat with some gentle climbs and easily avoidable obstacles.
properties.comment: Access track from car park at McLeans Forest, off McLeans Island Road

properties.description: A short loop walk through native bush. It is best accessed from the Summit Road layby below the old Jollies Bush stone shelter. The track can be used to connect with the Mt Pleasant Connector Track.

properties.routewarning: Control descending speed as many people walk this track. Graded 4 for steepness.
properties.description: A very steep historic track that is gravel surfaced, smooth and fast. Often used as an access track to the Port Hills trail system. Riders often use e-bikes to commute between Lyttelton and Heathcote Valley.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 4, advanced. Steep, narrow, poor traction, difficult to avoid obstacles. Exposed.
properties.comment: Start at the car park at the Heathcote Valley side of the end of Bridle Path in Lyttelton.

properties.description: A short loop walk through native bush. It is best accessed from the Summit Road layby below the old Jollies Bush stone shelter. The track can be used to connect with the Mt Pleasant Connector Track.
The first section is on a single track with some technical rocky sections. Descend gradually to Evans Pass to join the Godley Head Track on the other side of Evans Pass on Godley Head Road.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 4, advanced. Steep, narrow, poor traction, difficult to avoid obstacles. Exposed.
properties.comment: In a car park 200 m from the top of Mt Pleasant Road.

properties.routewarning: Control speed, walkers present
properties.description: The track is situated in tussock grassland and makes its way through the rocky bluffs in places. The track can be ridden in both directions. Descending riders should give way.
properties.mountainbikeclassification: Grade 4, advanced. Steep, narrow, poor traction, difficult to avoid obstacles. Exposed
properties.comment: From Sumnervale Reserve at the bottom or Evans Pass on the Summit Road.
